@endnode

@node install "How to install LCD Clock"
Installation of LCD Clock is simple. All you really need is the main
executable (LCD_Clock). Just put in into any directory you wish.
@endnode

@node usage "How to use LCD Clock"
LCD Clock can be started from the CLI or from Workbench. The command syntax is:

LCD_Clock.exe A=ACOL,B=BCOL,C=CCOL,RGB/S,PUBSCREEN

Where:
Ę ACOL, BCOL and CCOL mean the colour values for:
  A: The background
  B: Non-lit crystals
  C: Lit crystals
Ę RGB is a switch. If you omit it, the colour values will be regarded as actual
  palette indices. If you supply it, they will be regarded as 24-bit RGB values
  and tried to match as closely as possible.
Ę PUBSCREEN is the name of the public screen you wish to display the clock on.
  If this screen is not found, LCD Clock falls back to the Workbench screen.
  Remember, public screen names are case sensitive!
The values can be entered in either decimal or hexadecimal. For hexadecimal
values, enter an $ before the number (eg. $AABBCC).

Default values are indices 1, 3 and 2 for index mode (looks sort-of neat on a
standard 4-colour Workbench) and a simple green display for RGB mode.

Version 1.1 can also be started right from its icon on Workbench. There it reads
its settings from its icon's tool types. The tool types take the same form as
the command line arguments.
When started from the CLI, the command line arguments are used, regardless of
the icon's tool types.
@endnode

@node require "LCD Clock's requirements"
LCD Clock really doesn't require much. All it needs is the following:
Ę An Amiga« computer
Ę At least version 2.0 of Workbench (it MIGHT work on versions 1.2 or 1.3, but I
  haven't tested it)
Ę About 100 kb of free memory (nowadays, when few people have under 8 Mb of
  total memory, that shouldn't be a problem)
Ę Electricity
@endnode

